            </rs> or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag123"
                ref="#chemical_119"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag123">
          Zeolite
          
        </term>
            </rs>.- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag124"
                ref="#chemical_119"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag124">
          Zeolite
          
        </term>
            </rs> indeed<lb/>
often occurs in it, in large Cavities.-<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance </hi>.<lb/>
- There are certain general rules<lb/>
with regard to the indications of<lb/>
Metals, which will apply equally,<lb/>
to the productions in the primary<lb/>
&amp; the Secondary Rocks.-<lb/>
- Whenever a vein of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag125"
                ref="#chemical_102"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag125">
          Quartz
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
Spar, or any other white substance<lb/>
near the surface, contains in its<lb/>
cavities much <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">brown powder</hi> or dust,<lb/>
there is always a great probability,<lb/>
that <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a metallic</del> ore will be found<lb/>
at no great <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">distance</hi>.-<lb/>
- This brown powder is <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag126"
                ref="#chemical_008"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag126">
          Iron
          
        </term>
            </rs> in a<lb/>
particular state, which almost<lb/>
always accompanies <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag127"
                ref="#chemical_009"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag127">
          lead
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag128"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag128">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
- A green colour in a vein of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag129" ref="#chemical_102" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag129">
          Quartz
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi> or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">spar</hi>, likewise, generally<lb/>
indicates that metallic ore is at<lb/>
no great distance; &amp; it is usually<lb/>
connected with <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag130"
                ref="#chemical_032"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag130">
          pyrites
          
        </term>
            </rs> or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag131"
                ref="#chemical_038"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag131">
          Tin
          
        </term>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
- A dull green substance of this<lb/>
kind, in the Cornish &amp; Saxon Mines<lb/>
is often found in the same vein<lb/>
with <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag132"
                ref="#chemical_038"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag132">
          Tin
          
        </term>
            </rs>, it is a variety of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag133"
