               <term xml:id="tag138">
          carbonate<lb/>of barytes
          
        </term>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
- These are indications of Metals,<lb/>
when veins are distinct, &amp; laid<lb/>
bare in any of their parts.- but<lb/>
there are other indications, which<lb/>
require more <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">extensive geological</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">observations</hi>, though in general,<lb/>
they have been considered only<lb/>
after <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">partial views</hi>. &amp; applied<lb/>
only, by the habitual &amp;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">practical tact</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Miner</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
5<lb/>
- Metallic veins are often discovered<lb/>
by the loose materials which have<lb/>
been detached from them by decomposition<lb/>
from the action of water &amp; air in the<lb/>
lapse of time,- &amp; the method of<lb/>
searching for metals by examining<lb/>
the detached stones, in the soil of<lb/>
a valley, or in a chasm on the<lb/>
side of a hill, is called in<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag139"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag139" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs> where it is most practised<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Shodeing </hi>.-<lb/>
- In this district the only<lb/>
Metal known in early times was<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag140"
                ref="#chemical_038"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag140">
          Tin
          
        </term>
            </rs>, &amp; till after the establishment<lb/>
of the <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Norman <add>
                  <unclear>
                     <del rend="strikethrough">Neacdxxxxx</del>
                  </unclear>
               </add>
            </add> dynasty, even <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag141" ref="#chemical_038" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag141">
          Tin
          
        </term>
               </rs> ore</hi>
            <lb/>
was unknown as a production of<lb/>
veins; &amp; it was raised from the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag142"
                ref="#chemical_364"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag142">
          alluvial
          
        </term>
            </rs> depositions in vallies, &amp;<lb/>
separated in consequence of its<lb/>
specific weight from the Earthy<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
matters in mixtures - And it<lb/>
is this method which is described<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag143"
                ref="#person_448"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag143" type="person">
          Diodorus Siculus
        </name>
            </rs> "These Men"<lb/>
says he, alluding to the Cornish<lb/>
Britons, manufacture their <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag144"
                ref="#chemical_038"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag144">
          Tin
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
by working the grounds that produce<lb/>
it with great Art.- For though the<lb/>
Land is rocky, yet it has soft<lb/>
layers in it, in which the treasure<lb/>
is found.- whence the miners separate<lb/>
it, melt it &amp; purify it."-<lb/>
- But in proportion as <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag145"
                ref="#chemical_038"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag145">
          Tin
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
ore became more rare in the<lb/>
beds of rivers, &amp; in the lowlands,<lb/>
the search for it as extended<lb/>
into the soil that covers the<lb/>
hills, &amp; the original veins<lb/>
were in consequence discovered,<lb/>
&amp; the manner of tracing them<lb/>
by their detached productions<lb/>
has been ever since in common<lb/>
use.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
- Indications of Metallic Ores<lb/>
are often furnished by the impregnations<lb/>
in water issuing from the Springs in<lb/>
metalliferous strata.- Impregnations<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag146"
                ref="#chemical_008"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag146">
          iron
          
        </term>
            </rs>, &amp; of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag147"
