                xml:id="ttag148"
                ref="#chemical_008"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag148">
          iron
          
        </term>
            </rs> or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag149"
                ref="#chemical_323"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag149">
          Steel
          
        </term>
            </rs> to the fluid.<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>
            <lb/>
- A remarkable instance of the<lb/>
discovery of Metallic veins from<lb/>
these circumstances, lately occurred<lb/>
in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag150"
                ref="#place_436"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag150" type="place">
          North Wales
        </name>
            </rs>.- At the foot<lb/>
of a hill near <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag151"
                ref="#place_447"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag151" type="place">
          Dolgethly
        </name>
            </rs>, the<lb/>
water is highly impregnated with<lb/>
a salt of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag152"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag152">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs>; so highly, that<lb/>
the peat of a bog, into which it<lb/>
has discharged itself, is sufficiently<lb/>
loaded with the metal to afford<lb/>
it advantageously by burning.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
- When I was on the spot<lb/>
in June 1805, I observed that<lb/>
the vegetation was considerably<lb/>
injured upon the course of the<lb/>
Springs, &amp; the only plant that<lb/>
seemed to flourish near them<lb/>
was the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag153"
                ref="#misc_406"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag153">
          Statice
        </term>
            </rs>. All the<lb/>
circumstances appeared to point<lb/>
out distinctly the directions of the<lb/>
veins &amp; I have been informed,<lb/>
that by pursuing the indications,<lb/>
a considerable <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag154"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag154">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs> mine, has<lb/>
been discovered, &amp; is now<lb/>
advantageously worked.-<lb/>
- Wherever in a mining Country<lb/>
indeed, peculiar spots unnaturally<lb/>
sterile are perceived, there is great<lb/>
reason to suppose that the effect<lb/>
has some connexion with the<lb/>
presence of veins of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag155"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag155">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs> or of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag156"
                ref="#chemical_008"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag156">
          Iron
          
        </term>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
6<lb/>
- The effects of metallic impregnations<lb/>
in destroying vegetation, is evident<lb/>
from the general barrenness &amp;<lb/>
dreariness of mining districts, than<lb/>
which nothing can well be conceived<lb/>
more disagreeable to the eye.-<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">- I shall shew a sketch of a</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mining Country near <rs xml:id="ttag157" ref="#place_1009" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag157" type="place">
          Redruth
        </name>
               </rs> in</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <rs xml:id="ttag158" ref="#place_021" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag158" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
               </rs>.</del>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance.</hi>
            <lb/>
- No plants, except short &amp; dark<lb/>
green or brown <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag159"
                ref="#misc_122"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag159">
          Furze
        </term>
            </rs>; &amp; a heath<lb/>
that has scarcely sufficient vigour<lb/>
to produce flowers.- And this<lb/>
happens generally; |_ <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Where</hi> great<lb/>
treasures are found below the<lb/>
surface, there is neither fertility<lb/>
nor beauty above.- And the<lb/>
lines which Poet<lb/>
has unjustly applied to the most<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="22"
                xml:id="pb-22"
                facs="#i22"/>
            <lb/>
picturesque, if not the most fertile<lb/>
part of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag160"
                ref="#place_159"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag160" type="place">
          Britain
        </name>
            </rs>, may with propriety<lb/>
be quoted with regard to such<lb/>
a spot as <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">this</del>. the mining districts<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag161"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag161" type="place">
          cornwal
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
"<rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag162"
                ref="#otherwork_115"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag162">
            Far as the eye could reach
        </bibl>
            </rs>, no tree was seen,<lb/>
Earth clad in russet, scorned the lively green;<lb/>
The plague of Locusts, they secure defy,<lb/>
For in three hours a grasshopper must die."<lb/>
- There is an idea particularly<lb/>
prevalent amongst the Cornish Miners,<lb/>
that metallic veins are sometimes<lb/>
indicated by the appearance<lb/>
of fires in the night, over the<lb/>
places in which they exist.- This<lb/>
notion has been generally considered<lb/>
as a mere delusion.- but I am<lb/>
convinced from many observations,<lb/>
that it is not without foundation:<lb/>
it is easy to assign a reason for<lb/>
the phenomenon.- The metallic ores<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="23"
                xml:id="pb-23"
                facs="#i23"/>
            <lb/>
are for the most part perfect conductors<lb/>
of Electricity, &amp; when the Atmosphere<lb/>
is highly <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">loaded with</del> Electrical <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">matter,</del>
            <lb/>
the slow discharge of it, when it takes<lb/>
place above metallic veins, must<lb/>
necessarily produce a luminous<lb/>
appearance on their surfaces.-<lb/>
- This indication however, is as<lb/>
likely to apply to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag163"
                ref="#chemical_032"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag163">
          pyrites
          
        </term>
            </rs> or refractory<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag164"
                ref="#chemical_008"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag164">
          Iron
          
        </term>
            </rs> ore, as to the ores of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag165"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag165">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
or Silver; &amp; the former substances,<lb/>
are much the most abundant in<lb/>
nature.-<lb/>
- Of the numerous mysterious<lb/>
practices, supposed to be connected<lb/>
with the discovery of Mines, almost<lb/>
the only relict is, the search by the<lb/>
divining Rod, &amp; the belief in this<lb/>
is rapidly going out of fashion, even<lb/>
amongst the common Miners.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="24"
                xml:id="pb-24"
                facs="#i24"/>
            <lb/>
- The divining Rod is a forked stick<lb/>
of hazel, which when held horizontally,<lb/>
a branch being in each hand, was<lb/>
supposed to be attracted by Metals.-<lb/>
- Most of the ancient writers on<lb/>
Metallurgy, have given long Theories<lb/>
to account for the efficacy of the rod,<lb/>
&amp; even as late as 1778, M<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">r</hi>.. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag166"
                ref="#person_466"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag166" type="person">
          Pryce
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
in his "<rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag167"
                ref="#otherwork_217"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag167">
            History of the Cornish Mines
        </bibl>
            </rs>",<lb/>
states his full belief in its powers;<lb/>
And explains them by supposing that<lb/>
certain steams or vapours, rise from mines;<lb/>
though he does not make it very clear,<lb/>
why the hazel &amp; no other substance<lb/>
should have such a particular<lb/>
affection for these effluvia.-<lb/>
- The divining rod, it is well<lb/>
known, is applied to the discovery<lb/>
of Springs of water, as well as of<lb/>
metallic veins; &amp; there are<lb/>
very respectable &amp; excellent Persons<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
7<lb/>
who believe in this power, &amp; that they<lb/>
themselves are capable of exercising it.<lb/>
- Nothing should be disbelieved,<lb/>
because it is marvellous, because<lb/>
it does not coincide with our received<lb/>
opinions.- The business of Philosophy<lb/>
is to investigate <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">causes</hi>.- A few<lb/>
years ago, the fall of stones from<lb/>
above, appeared a mere fable,<lb/>
yet accurate observation has confirmed<lb/>
the fact by a collection of testimonies<lb/>
that it is impossible for a candid<lb/>
mind to question.- A very<lb/>
few observations, will be sufficient<lb/>
to enlighten this subject of the<lb/>
divining Rod; to shew what<lb/>
is possible; &amp; what must of<lb/>
necessity be unfounded.-<lb/>
- There are Persons so<lb/>
susceptible of Electrical impressions<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
as to be affected by the approach<lb/>
of a thunder storm with peculiar<lb/>
unpleasant sensations; or even<lb/>
by the excitement of a common<lb/>
machine:- And large masses of<lb/>
metallic substances, &amp; a moist<lb/>
stratum of Earth, being Conductors<lb/>
of Electricity, will necessarily influence<lb/>
the electrical state of the atmosphere;<lb/>
&amp; may produce <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">an effect</hi>, on very<lb/>
delicate organs, possibly a peculiar<lb/>
sensation on the surface of the Skin.-<lb/>
- But the bending of the hazel twig,<lb/>
can only be produced by the muscular<lb/>
power of the hands:- The inert<lb/>
vegetable fibres can not be<lb/>
made to twist round either by<lb/>
weak Electricity, or moisture,<lb/>
or metallic steams.- This<lb/>
effect is merely connected<lb/>
either with a real or an<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
imaginary impression on the nerves,<lb/>
which might be as easily associated<lb/>
with the twisting of the fingers, or<lb/>
closing the Eyelids, or any other<lb/>
arbitary muscular motion.-<lb/>
- Again, there is generally<lb/>
a false idea with respect to the<lb/>
manner in which water exists below<lb/>
the surface.- It is vulgarly supposed<lb/>
that it fills cavities in the Earth;<lb/>
whereas in all common cases, it is<lb/>
merely distributed through a stratum<lb/>
of gravel, or sand, or clay; &amp; there<lb/>
is no collection of water, till an<lb/>
excavation is made, &amp; the central<lb/>
part of the moist stratum is the<lb/>
part where the water would most<lb/>
readily collect; but water would<lb/>
likewise flow into any Cavity made<lb/>
in any part of the Stratum, so<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
that the idea of selecting a particular<lb/>
limited spot for water is absurd;<lb/>
&amp; at a certain depth below the<lb/>
surface, water may always be<lb/>
found.-<lb/>
- A vein or a mass of metal,<lb/>
is much more definite &amp; limited;<lb/>
yet the divining rod usually fails<lb/>
applied to this mode of discovery;<lb/>
&amp; if there be sensations connected<lb/>
with the Electrical effects of<lb/>
